480
00:33:01,794 --> 00:33:03,835
Says he specializes in wills and trusts.

481
00:33:04,752 --> 00:33:07,377
<i>He goes from criminal prosecution to wills and trusts?</i>

482
00:33:07,544 --> 00:33:09,919
<i>He's been there 17 years, he's not a partner?</i>

483
00:33:10,085 --> 00:33:13,752
<i>This is the guy they send?
Who is this guy?</i>

484
00:33:28,002 --> 00:33:30,252
- Hi.
- Close the door.

485
00:33:30,710 --> 00:33:34,710
All right. So nobody, none of you,
had any idea he was coming?

486
00:33:35,294 --> 00:33:37,127
To Milwaukee? For a deposition?

487
00:33:37,335 --> 00:33:40,877
We thought there was a settlement.
There's been some rumors.

488
00:33:41,044 --> 00:33:45,627
Okay. Look, it's very simple.
Arthur has a chemical imbalance.

489
00:33:45,835 --> 00:33:49,669
He's supposed to be taking his medication.
He's fallen behind on that.

490
00:33:49,835 --> 00:33:52,335
He's on the mend.
He'll be fine in three or four days.

491
00:33:52,502 --> 00:33:56,669
Now, I wanna make this crystal clear.
What happened here stays in this room.

492
00:33:56,835 --> 00:33:59,835
This is not a piece of information
you wanna be out in front of.

493
00:34:00,002 --> 00:34:03,294
Anybody has a problem with that, I need to know right now.

494
00:34:04,419 --> 00:34:05,794
All right.

495
00:34:06,669 --> 00:34:08,460
We're stuck here overnight.

496
00:34:08,669 --> 00:34:10,960
I'm gonna take him home tomorrow if I can.

497
00:34:11,127 --> 00:34:13,085
Who's in charge of the deposition schedule?

498
00:34:13,252 --> 00:34:14,919
- I am.
- Where do we stand with that?

499
00:34:15,085 --> 00:34:17,294
I guess it's on hold.
We didn't know what to do.

500
00:34:17,460 --> 00:34:19,502
Nothing is on hold.
Keep doing what you were.

501
00:34:19,669 --> 00:34:21,960
Other side wants to talk, they can call New York.

502
00:34:22,127 --> 00:34:25,169
- I need his briefcase.
- Arthur's? I don't-- I didn't see it.

503
00:34:25,335 --> 00:34:28,460
- He said it was in the room.
- It might be the stuff Jody grabbed.

504
00:34:28,835 --> 00:34:30,419
Find it.

505
00:34:36,377 --> 00:34:40,669
So all these people, they all start
having these dreams, okay?

506
00:34:40,835 --> 00:34:45,252
You know what a vision quest is?
You know, for, like, Navajos and stuff?

507
00:34:45,419 --> 00:34:48,669
<i>Yeah. I think so. Like a....</i>

508
00:34:49,044 --> 00:34:50,919
<i>Like a special dream.</i>

509
00:34:51,085 --> 00:34:55,627
Except this is like a whole bunch of people
having the same dream.

510
00:34:55,835 --> 00:34:59,210
They're all having this dream
that they should go to this one place.

511
00:34:59,377 --> 00:35:01,419
They don't know why or anything.

512
00:35:01,585 --> 00:35:04,710
They just have this feeling that they have to go there.

513
00:35:04,877 --> 00:35:06,752
<i>That they've been summoned.</i>

514
00:35:06,919 --> 00:35:08,127
That's the chapter.

515
00:35:08,335 --> 00:35:11,294
Seriously, that's what it's called:
"Summons to Conquest."

516
00:35:11,460 --> 00:35:12,752
<i>That's the title.</i>

517
00:35:12,919 --> 00:35:18,585
Yeah, but do they know? Do they know
they're all having the same dream?

518
00:35:18,752 --> 00:35:20,710
<i>No. That's what's so cool.</i>

519
00:35:21,252 --> 00:35:23,169
They all think it's just them.

520
00:35:23,335 --> 00:35:27,419
That maybe they're, like, going crazy
or something, so they don't wanna admit it.

521
00:35:27,585 --> 00:35:29,710
Yeah, but they're not crazy, are they?

522
00:35:29,877 --> 00:35:33,377
<i>No. It's real. It's really happening.</i>

523
00:35:33,544 --> 00:35:37,169
Yeah, it is happening, isn't it?

524
00:35:38,377 --> 00:35:43,044
Something larger than themselves
and they're not ready, are they...

525
00:35:43,210 --> 00:35:45,002
...to hear it?

526
00:35:45,169 --> 00:35:47,085
Yeah. But later they will.

527
00:35:47,252 --> 00:35:50,085
So if you're gonna read it, I don't wanna spoil it.

528
00:35:51,669 --> 00:35:53,502
What are you doing?
Who you talking to?

529
00:35:53,669 --> 00:35:55,669
<i>I called my dad. It's a friend of his.</i>

530
00:35:55,835 --> 00:35:59,085
<i>- Who?
- Mr. Edens. You don't know him.</i>

531
00:35:59,252 --> 00:36:01,919
<i>- Hello? Hello?
- Henry, it's after 11.</i>

532
00:36:02,085 --> 00:36:03,877
<i>I gotta get off now.</i>

533
00:36:04,044 --> 00:36:08,044
No. Wait, wait. The book.
I need the book. The title.

534
00:36:08,669 --> 00:36:10,877
<i>The book is Realm and Conquest.</i>

535
00:36:11,044 --> 00:36:12,835
Realm and Conquest.

536
00:36:13,002 --> 00:36:16,044
- It's Book One, with the red cover.
- Henry, give me the phone.

537
00:36:16,210 --> 00:36:18,794
I gotta go. Tell my dad I called. Okay?

538
00:36:19,669 --> 00:36:24,044
Yeah. Yeah. Thank-- Thank-- Thank--
Thank you, Henry, thank you.

539
00:36:28,252 --> 00:36:31,669
<i>Realm and Conquest. Thank you.</i>

540
00:36:54,877 --> 00:36:56,919
Karen? Hi, I'm Michael Clayton.

541
00:36:57,085 --> 00:36:58,544
- You're late.
- I know.

542
00:36:58,710 --> 00:37:01,252
I'm sorry, it was more complicated than we thought.

543
00:37:01,419 --> 00:37:03,127
Where is he?
We've been here since 5:30.

544
00:37:03,294 --> 00:37:05,460
- He's asleep.
- Well, wake him up.

545
00:37:05,627 --> 00:37:07,877
That's not gonna happen.
We just got him sedated.

546
00:37:08,377 --> 00:37:11,419
Once he gets back on his regular medication...

547
00:37:11,585 --> 00:37:13,544
...then it's just a matter of time.

548
00:37:13,710 --> 00:37:16,460
- Have you seen the video? The tape?
- I heard about it.

549
00:37:16,710 --> 00:37:19,210
What happened after is worse.

550
00:37:19,377 --> 00:37:23,252
This is in the parking lot, okay?
People running for their cars.

551
00:37:23,419 --> 00:37:25,544
He's there in his socks, nothing else.

552
00:37:25,710 --> 00:37:29,377
"I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.
I will not sit with this sickness any longer.

553
00:37:29,544 --> 00:37:32,335
I cannot aid this sickness any longer."

554
00:37:32,544 --> 00:37:34,127
What does this mean?

555
00:37:34,544 --> 00:37:36,085
I'm not sure.

556
00:37:36,252 --> 00:37:38,877
You've been with him the whole evening.
What's he saying?

557
00:37:39,044 --> 00:37:40,835
He wasn't really making much sense.

558
00:37:41,044 --> 00:37:42,585
This is totally unacceptable.

559
00:37:42,752 --> 00:37:45,710
This is a 3-billion-dollar
class-action lawsuit.

560
00:37:45,877 --> 00:37:47,794
In the morning, I have to call my board.

561
00:37:47,960 --> 00:37:52,502
I have to tell them that the architect
of our entire defense has been arrested...

562
00:37:52,710 --> 00:37:56,835
...for running naked in a snowstorm,
chasing the plaintiffs through a parking lot.

563
00:37:57,044 --> 00:37:58,835
I understand.

564
00:37:59,877 --> 00:38:01,919
What sickness is he talking about?

565
00:38:02,085 --> 00:38:04,710
- I don't know. It could be anything.
- Well, give me one.

566
00:38:04,877 --> 00:38:06,210
Frostbite.

567
00:38:06,710 --> 00:38:08,335
You think this is funny?

568
00:38:08,502 --> 00:38:10,752
Look, his wife was sick and she died last year.

569
00:38:10,919 --> 00:38:15,377
His daughter doesn't talk to him.
He's all alone. All he does is your case.

570
00:38:15,544 --> 00:38:18,252
He skipped his pills.
He had a bad day. That's it.

571
00:38:18,419 --> 00:38:21,127
And you're somehow the authority on this?

572
00:38:21,835 --> 00:38:24,335
His last episode was eight years ago.
I was there.

573
00:38:24,544 --> 00:38:27,377
I helped bring him home.
I watched him get better. That's it.

574
00:38:27,544 --> 00:38:31,294
Come on, Karen, you didn't hire this guy
because of his low-key regularity...

575
00:38:31,460 --> 00:38:34,460
...you hired him because he's a killer,
because he's brilliant...

576
00:38:34,627 --> 00:38:37,294
...because he's crazy enough
to grind away on this case...

577
00:38:37,460 --> 00:38:40,210
- ...for six years without a break.
- We pay for his time.

578
00:38:40,377 --> 00:38:42,419
I thought you wanted an explanation.

579
00:38:42,585 --> 00:38:45,335
In the morning, I'm calling Marty Bach.

580
00:38:45,502 --> 00:38:48,502
But, then, you know that.
Thank you, Michael.

581
00:38:54,377 --> 00:38:56,502
He was mostly just quiet.

582
00:38:56,669 --> 00:38:59,544
I heard him moving around,
I gave him a pill 15 minutes ago.

583
00:38:59,710 --> 00:39:02,169
- He took it?
- A deal's a deal, right?

584
00:39:02,377 --> 00:39:04,085
A super job, Elston.

585
00:39:04,252 --> 00:39:07,919
You get to New York, you need tickets
to the game or anything, you let me know.

586
00:39:08,085 --> 00:39:09,544
I'll do that for sure.

587
00:39:29,877 --> 00:39:31,544
Did you see her?

588
00:39:31,877 --> 00:39:34,044
- Who?
- Anna.

589
00:39:34,585 --> 00:39:35,960
No.

590
00:39:37,169 --> 00:39:40,669
No, I didn't see her.
She probably went back to the farm.

591
00:39:41,585 --> 00:39:43,210
Well, we need her.

592
00:39:45,085 --> 00:39:49,877
Marty, even then, and the rest of them,
they won't understand.

593
00:39:50,919 --> 00:39:54,460
Well, if anybody can explain it to them, it's you, Arthur.

594
00:39:56,169 --> 00:39:58,377
No, they're lost.

595
00:39:58,544 --> 00:40:01,585
- They have what they want.
- Let it go, man.

596
00:40:01,752 --> 00:40:03,585
This what you wanted?

597
00:40:05,210 --> 00:40:06,669
To be a janitor?

598
00:40:07,169 --> 00:40:10,210
Live like this? All this?

599
00:40:11,044 --> 00:40:12,710
Do what you do?

600
00:40:13,585 --> 00:40:15,502
It can't be.

601
00:40:16,377 --> 00:40:17,377
It's....

602
00:40:17,585 --> 00:40:21,210
It's a burden, that's what I'm trying to tell you.

603
00:40:21,835 --> 00:40:23,960
That's-- That's how it feels.

604
00:40:24,919 --> 00:40:29,585
Well, I know that we've been summoned.

605
00:40:31,377 --> 00:40:33,210
Get some sleep.

606
00:40:49,085 --> 00:40:50,085
<i>Hello?</i>

607
00:40:50,252 --> 00:40:54,044
Yes. Hi, I'm looking for Verne?

608
00:40:55,085 --> 00:40:56,419
<i>You have a number?</i>

609
00:40:56,585 --> 00:40:59,710
Don Jeffries gave me the number.
He said I could call at any time.

610
00:40:59,877 --> 00:41:01,752
<i>No. The account number.</i>

611
00:41:01,919 --> 00:41:06,085
The code? I do.
I have it right here. One moment.

612
00:41:08,044 --> 00:41:10,044
Excuse me one moment.

613
00:41:10,502 --> 00:41:14,085
It's right here. 12-BKR-6.

614
00:41:14,252 --> 00:41:16,335
12-BKR-6.

615
00:41:17,752 --> 00:41:19,752
Am I speaking with Verne?

616
00:41:20,877 --> 00:41:22,169
<i>It's Mr. Verne.</i>

617
00:41:22,335 --> 00:41:25,669
Mr. Verne. I'm sorry, it's so late.

618
00:41:25,835 --> 00:41:27,835
Don said that I could....

619
00:41:29,544 --> 00:41:31,752
I'm not exactly sure how this works.

620
00:41:31,919 --> 00:41:33,919
<i>Do you have e-mail
at your current location?</i>

621
00:41:34,085 --> 00:41:35,335
I do.

622
00:41:35,502 --> 00:41:37,669
<i>- Are you alone?
- I am.</i>

623
00:41:38,419 --> 00:41:42,669
<i>Okay, I'm gonna upload you
a little encryption package we like to use.</i>

624
00:41:42,835 --> 00:41:44,252
<i>It's pretty self-explanatory.</i>

625
00:41:44,419 --> 00:41:45,710
<i>- Okay.
- Okay.</i>

626
00:41:45,877 --> 00:41:48,835
<i>But you have to give me a minute
to get to my desk. Hold on.</i>

627
00:41:49,002 --> 00:41:50,710
Okay. Thank you.

628
00:42:14,919 --> 00:42:17,585
<i>What I was wondering is...</i>

629
00:42:17,752 --> 00:42:20,585
...I have an option on the lease
for six more years.

630
00:42:20,752 --> 00:42:23,419
I was wondering if there's any way I could lay that off.

631
00:42:23,585 --> 00:42:26,585
Is the lease worth anything?

632
00:42:30,085 --> 00:42:32,544
Eighty-nine hundred a month. It's--

633
00:42:33,002 --> 00:42:35,752
The fixtures are gone, but there's--

634
00:42:37,419 --> 00:42:40,627
But there's the bar, there's a kitchen,
it's a great space.

635
00:42:42,210 --> 00:42:43,752
But there's a--

636
00:42:48,085 --> 00:42:51,169
Yeah, I understand. No, I understand.

637
00:42:52,960 --> 00:42:55,044
Okay, yeah, I will.

638
00:42:55,669 --> 00:42:57,210
All right. Thanks.

639
00:43:07,544 --> 00:43:09,127
Come on, Arthur.

640
00:43:11,752 --> 00:43:13,044
Arthur!

641
00:43:14,502 --> 00:43:15,585
Arthur, open the door.

642
00:43:19,169 --> 00:43:21,044
Arthur, open the door!

643
00:43:23,877 --> 00:43:26,252
Arthur, open the goddamn door!

644
00:43:27,585 --> 00:43:28,835
Arthur, op--!

645
00:43:29,627 --> 00:43:31,752
Open the fucking door!

646
00:43:38,127 --> 00:43:39,585
Arthur!

647
00:43:40,377 --> 00:43:43,002
Goddamn it, Arthur! Open the fucking--!

648
00:43:53,460 --> 00:43:54,627
Arthur?!

649
00:44:05,960 --> 00:44:07,752
- Mr. Verne, hey.
- Hey, Danny.

650
00:44:07,960 --> 00:44:10,210
You guys are early.
I was pulling the other bags.

651
00:44:10,377 --> 00:44:13,252
You can put them back.
There's been a change of plans, sorry.

652
00:44:13,419 --> 00:44:15,294
- We ready?
- Yep.

653
00:44:19,460 --> 00:44:21,502
For chrissake.

654
00:44:21,669 --> 00:44:23,544
Don Jeffries signed this?

655
00:44:24,002 --> 00:44:26,585
That's really his signature?

656
00:44:26,752 --> 00:44:28,710
Where's the original?

657
00:44:28,877 --> 00:44:33,919
We had a warehouse fire five years ago.
We lost a number of documents.

658
00:44:40,044 --> 00:44:42,919
What the hell is this doing in Arthur's bag?

659
00:44:43,544 --> 00:44:45,085
Well, I don't know, Marty.

660
00:44:45,252 --> 00:44:49,210
That's something I was hoping
you might be able to tell me.

661
00:44:53,960 --> 00:44:55,544
What are we looking for?

662
00:44:55,710 --> 00:44:59,919
If it says U/North, pull it aside.
Anything that says U/North.

663
00:45:01,377 --> 00:45:02,877
What a mess this is.

664
00:45:07,502 --> 00:45:08,752
I want all this...

665
00:45:09,669 --> 00:45:13,752
...everything here, I want it all packed up
and sent up to the house.

666
00:45:14,877 --> 00:45:16,294
Any luck, Michael?

667
00:45:17,002 --> 00:45:21,127
He booked a limo from Newark Airport at 3,
got out at West Fourth Street...

668
00:45:21,294 --> 00:45:23,252
...tipped the driver 100 bucks
and walked away.

669
00:45:23,419 --> 00:45:24,627
Did you try his apartment?

670
00:45:24,794 --> 00:45:25,919
- He moved.
- I know.

671
00:45:26,127 --> 00:45:28,460
It's a loft. No doorman.
I rang, nobody answered.

672
00:45:28,627 --> 00:45:31,294
- I called, I got the machine.
- So he could be anywhere.

673
00:45:31,460 --> 00:45:34,460
Arthur downtown is not a good idea.
Some goddamn loft.

674
00:45:34,627 --> 00:45:37,377
- Where's his daughter?
- I don't know. Spain, lndia.

675
00:45:37,544 --> 00:45:40,669
Mars. She's crazier than he'll ever be.

676
00:45:40,835 --> 00:45:42,669
Barry's taking over on U/North.

677
00:45:42,835 --> 00:45:44,627
We got a lot of groveling to do.

678
00:45:44,794 --> 00:45:46,919
You didn't exactly charm Karen Crowder.

679
00:45:47,085 --> 00:45:48,294
I was punting.

680
00:45:48,502 --> 00:45:51,127
You gotta saddle up here and get things under control.

681
00:45:51,335 --> 00:45:52,294
Saddle up?

682
00:45:52,502 --> 00:45:55,544
He needs to be under a doctor's care.
He needs to be admitted.

683
00:45:55,710 --> 00:45:58,044
- Where?
- Does that really matter?

684
00:45:58,210 --> 00:46:01,127
Michael, U/North needs to know he's under control.

685
00:46:01,294 --> 00:46:04,627
He's in a facility. They've been shook up.
They need to be reassured.

686
00:46:04,835 --> 00:46:07,002
- It's not gonna be that easy.
- Why the hell not?

687
00:46:07,169 --> 00:46:10,960
Because the laws in New York are
pretty tough on involuntary commitment.

688
00:46:11,169 --> 00:46:12,710
